Joseph Olaouwa The Accident Investigation Bureau on Thursday vowed to investigate a collision involving the Middle East Airline aircraft and a Turkish plane at the Muritala Mohammed International Airport, Lagos. The incident occurred on Wednesday when an Airbus A330-243 operated by the MEA ran into a Turkish cargo aircraft with registration number TC-LJC parked at the international apron, clipping the tail cone of the Turkish aircraft. A statement from the AIB’s General Manager, Public Affairs, Tunji Oketumbi, described the incident as serious, noting that a formal report would be published regarding the incident. The statement made available to our correspondent on Thursday was and titled “Press release on Turkish Airline and Middle East Airline Ground Collision Occurrence.” It read, “Accident Investigation Bureau has been notified and has commenced investigation into a serious incident involving an Airbus A330-243 with the Nationality Registration Marks OD-MEA operated by Middle East Airline and a Boeing 777 with Nationality and Registration Marks TC-LJC  operated by Turkish Airline, which occurred on July 29, 2020 at the Murtala Muhammed International Airport, Lagos. “The Turkish cargo aircraft was parked at the international apron when the Middle East airbus was taxing before it ran into it, cutting through the tail cone and damaging part of the right horizontal stabilizer of the Turkish aircraft. “All passengers on the Middle East Airline had to disembark with no injury or fatality.” Copyright PUNCH. All rights reserved. This material, and other digital content on this website, may not be reproduced, published, broadcast, rewritten or redistributed in whole or in part without prior express written permission from PUNCH. Contact: theeditor@punchng.com 